Here is the code that meets the specifications:
```
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;

print "Welcome to the number guessing game!\n";
print "I'm thinking of a number between 1 and 100.\n";

my $number = 55; # Change this to a random number between 1 and 100
my $guess = 0;

while ($guess != $number) {
  print "Enter your guess: ";
  $guess = <STDIN>;
  chomp $guess;

  if ($guess > $number) {
    print "Your guess is too high. Try again.\n";
  } elsif ($guess < $number) {
    print "Your guess is too low. Try again.\n";
  } else {
    print "Congratulations! You guessed the number correctly.\n";
  }
}
```
Note that I've kept the hardcoded value of `$number` as 55, as per the specification. In a real-world implementation, you would want to use a random number generator to generate a random value for `$number`. You can use the `rand` function in Perl to achieve this, like this: `my $number = int(rand(100)) + 1;`.
